<HL>    Marketing & Media:
@  Murdoch's Interest in New York Post
@  Seems to Pose Dilemma for News Corp.
@  ----
@  By Patrick M. Reilly
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 03/25/93 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9 </SO>
<CO>    NWS </CO>
<IN> MEDIA (MED), PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. confirmed his interest in
buying back the ailing New York Post. But analysts said that if he
winds up bidding for the paper, he faces a no-win situation in the
overcrowded New York newspaper market.
</p>
<p>
   While Mr. Murdoch appears to have the money to keep the paper
going, investing in a troubled newspaper would seem at odds with
News Corp.'s current strategic moves away from newspapers and into
electronic news and information delivery, industry analysts said.
They also said that the Post may not survive long enough for Mr.
Murdoch to get the necessary approval to buy the paper, which he
owned from 1976 to 1988.
</p>
<p>
   Patrick Purcell, chief executive of News Corp.'s News America
Publishing unit, said yesterday, "We have been asked by various
public officials if we would consider taking a look at it, and we
are." He added, "Newspapers are something he Mr. Murdoch loves. I
don't think he has ever lost interest in them."
</p>
<p>
   But at issue is whether Mr. Murdoch can overcome federal
regulations that would prevent him from bidding for the Post. Under
Federal Communications Commission regulations prohibiting
crossownership, Mr. Murdoch is barred from owning both a newspaper
and television station in the same market. After Mr. Murdoch bought
the Post, he acquired local television station WNYW-TV in 1986, and
he was forced to sell the paper two years later.
</p>
<p>
   With some political maneuvering, Mr. Murdoch could be granted a
waiver from the FCC that would allow him to own the Post and his Fox
Broadcasting Co. network affiliate. "The cross-ownership issue is a
concern," Mr. Purcell conceded. "If there were an FCC waiver, we
would consider buying the Post."
</p>
<p>
   A Murdoch bid would compete with businessman Abraham Hirschfeld
who has an option to buy the unprofitable paper.
</p>
<p>
   The Post, which has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy-protection,
is estimated to have losses of $10 million a year under its current
owner, real estate developer Peter Kalikow; is losing circulation,
and faces increased competition from a rejuvenated New York Daily
News. Even News Corp.'s Mr. Purcell called the Post "a tough
financial situation."
</p>
<p>
   Analysts were puzzled by Mr. Murdoch's new interest in the paper.
"I just don't get it. I don't know what sort of synergy it
represents" said Jessica Reif, an analyst at Oppenheimer & Co.
</p>
</TXT>
