<HL>    IBM Appoints
@  Chrysler's York
@  As Finance Chief
@  ---
@  Computer Maker's Move
@  Signals Strategy of Cuts
@  In Its Costs, Asset Sales
@  ----
@  By Michael W. Miller and Douglas Lavin
@  Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 05/04/93 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3 </SO>
<CO>    C IBM </CO>
<IN> AUTOMOBILES (AUT), COMPUTERS (CPR) </IN>
<TXT>
<p>
   International Business Machines Corp. continued its executive
makeover by hiring Jerome B. York, an architect of the turnaround at
Chrysler Corp., to become chief financial officer.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. York, 54 years old, is a West Point graduate who helped
transform Chrysler by slashing costs and selling billions of dollars
in assets. His appointment is a strong sign that IBM's new chairman,
Louis V. Gerstner Jr., plans a similar strategy at the wounded
computer giant.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. Gerstner raced to hire Mr. York after meeting him for the
first time just three weeks ago in IBM's Manhattan offices. In his
first month, Mr. Gerstner has also brought in outsiders to run IBM's
communications and disk-drive business, and is searching for a new
head of personnel.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. York was executive vice president for finance and a board
member at Chrysler, where he spent 12 years in financial posts and
running several car and truck divisions. Chrysler didn't name a
successor yesterday. While it may look outside the company, it has
several inside candidates.
</p>
<p>
   A lean, intense man with a piercing stare, Mr. York was known at
Chrysler for his obsessive work hours, especially during the auto
maker's near-collapse in the late 1970s.
</p>
<p>
   "At one meeting in 1979, I turned to him to make a presentation
and he said, `Steve, you better handle this, I don't feel so good.'
Then he passed out and security guys had to come take him away on a
stretcher," recalled former Chrysler Vice Chairman Robert S. "Steve"
Miller. "It was just exhaustion from too many all-nighters, too much
coffee and cigarettes instead of the old sustenance."
</p>
<p>
   IBM's selection of Mr. York was first reported by USA Today.
</p>
<p>
   At IBM, Mr. York will face what he yesterday called "the most
challenging situation of this era." IBM had losses of nearly $5
billion last year and saw its stock price cut in half amid the nose
dive of its mainframe computer business.
</p>
<p>
   While IBM's balance sheet and core finances have remained stable,
it has lost much credibility on Wall Street and has been stripped of
its prized triple-A credit rating. Its longtime chief financial
officer, Frank Metz, took early retirement in the January executive
shake-up that also pushed aside ex-chairman John Akers.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. York will also be arriving at IBM amid charges by some
financial experts that the company is too aggressive about reporting
revenue that it may never actually get through complex sales
gimmicks and a rare leasing maneuver. In an April 7 Wall Street
Journal article, several experts suggested that IBM's accounting
grew much more liberal since the mid-1980s as its business turned
sour. IBM adamantly disputes these charges.
</p>
<p>
   In an interview yesterday, Mr. York wouldn't yet commit himself
to cost-cutting or any other specific strategy.
</p>
<p>
   "Reading the published financial data, IBM's costs don't appear
to me to be out of control," he said. "But on the other hand, if the
revenue side of the equation does not come back to former levels,
then probably there's going to have to be some reductions on the
cost side."
</p>
<p>
   Mr. York led the effort to control costs at Chrysler in the late
1980s, when, for the second time in a decade, the car giant faced a
financial crisis. With outdated products and bloated overhead,
Chrysler's earnings plunged from an operating profit of more than $1
billion in 1988 to an operating loss of $538 million in 1991.
</p>
<p>
   The company's unfunded pension liability soared and its credit
rating dropped below junk levels. Some analysts were predicting
Chrysler's demise as an independent auto maker.
</p>
<p>
   In response, Chrysler cut in half the time and money invested in
new car lines and wrung savings from cooperating more with
suppliers. It also pumped money into new products, including the
high-profile Neon, a small car it says it spent only $1.3 billion to
develop.
</p>
<p>
   The result was that last year Chrysler reported net of $723
million, the only Big Three auto maker to turn a profit. Its stock
has also soared from around $10 a share just two years ago. In New
York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, it was quoted at
$42.125, up 87.5 cents a share.
</p>
<p>
   Early this year Mr. York led Chrysler through one of the largest
stock sales ever for a U.S. industrial company, raising $1.78
billion. Chrysler is using most of the proceeds to reduce its $4.4
billion unfunded pension liability.
</p>
<p>
   IBM and Mr. York wouldn't discuss his compensation package, which
could easily reach into seven figures. The subject is sensitive at a
time when IBM is running big losses and laying off thousands of
employees. At last week's annual meeting, Mr. Gerstner faced angry
questions about his $3.5 million annual salary and bonus.
</p>
<p>
   Chrysler last year paid Mr. York $414,167 in salary, a $300,000
bonus and $327,621 in long-term compensation based on quality
improvements in the company's products. By contrast, IBM paid Mr.
Metz, its former chief financial officer, a total of $725,000 last
year.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. York also had stock options that Chrysler valued at $2.9
million at the end of 1992. Normally, IBM would be expected to give
Mr. York a one-time payment to cover the options he leaves behind.
</p>
<p>
   IBM launched its search for a financial officer in January, two
months before Mr. Gerstner arrived. With Mr. Akers a lame duck, vice
chairman and acting CFO Paul Rizzo ran the search.
</p>
<p>
   After Mr. Gerstner took over April 1, Mr. Rizzo and Russell
Reynolds Associates search consultant Andrew Hart presented the new
chairman with five finalists. Mr. Gerstner chose to interview only
two: Mr. York and another executive who wasn't identified.
</p>
<p>
   In Big Board trading, IBM shares were quoted at $49.25, up 62.5
cents, but analysts said the rise wasn't connected to the hiring of
Mr. York.
</p>
<p>
   At Chrysler, Mr. York had been a dark-horse candidate to succeed
departing chairman Lee A. Iacocca. Chrysler ultimately chose former
General Motors Corp. executive Robert Eaton. The succession struggle
left relations somewhat strained between Mr. York and Chrysler
President Robert Lutz, who had been another contender for the top
job.
</p>
<p>
   Chrysler said Mr. York's subordinates would report temporarily to
Mr. Eaton. Candidates from within Chrysler to succeed Mr. York
include Gary C. Valade, human resources chief; Thomas P. Capo,
treasurer; and Thomas W. Sidlik, vice president for customer
satisfaction and quality.
</p>
<p>
   After graduating from West Point, Mr. York got a masters in
structural engineering from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and an M.B.A. at the University of Michigan. A native of
Memphis, Tenn., he said he spends his spare time working as a
"gentleman farmer" and hunting deer, elk, and antelope.
</p>
</TXT>
