<HL>    Economy:
@  Group of Top Executives Urges Congress
@  To Pass Clinton's Deficit-Cutting Plan
@  ----
@  By Rick Wartzman
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 07/29/93 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2 </SO>
<CO>    ADM ARC BP BS C.PDV FMC ITT ML OAT OXY PRD PWJ RD SB SC SUN T.VO
   TGT TWX U.BP U.SLR UAL VO X.LZF XRX ZE </CO>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   A group of top corporate executives urged Congress
to pass President Clinton's deficit-reduction plan, declaring that
it is superior to the only apparent alternative: more gridlock.
</p>
<p>
   "There are things in the president's plan that I don't like and
things that aren't in there that I'd like to see," said Stephen
Wolf, chairman of UAL Corp.'s United Airlines. "But, on balance,
it's a significant step forward."
</p>
<p>
   Mr. Wolf, whose sentiments were widely shared by his colleagues,
joined 68 other executives who lunched with the president and then
assembled in the East Room of the White House in a show of support
for the Clinton program.
</p>
<p>
   The meeting went far beyond Mr. Clinton's normal weekly gathering
of business leaders. Economic adviser Gene Sperling described it as
"a true full-court press" to pass the deficit-reduction bill, the
final version of which is now being hammered out by House and Senate
negotiators.
</p>
<p>
   The executives' backing -- however tepid -- gives the
administration a way to counter business critics of the overall
package, while providing the White House and Treasury more levers to
win over reluctant lawmakers. Both parties are using business
leaders as proxies of sorts to put pressure on swing votes in the
Senate and House, and there has been sometimes intense
behind-the-scenes maneuvering to win, or block, endorsements from
CEOs.
</p>
<p>
   By having Bethlehem Steel Corp.'s Chairman Hank Barnette turn up
in the East Room, for example, Democrats are in a stronger position
to win over Rep. Paul McHale, a Pennsylvania freshman from the
steelmaker's home town who voted against the deficit package when it
first passed the House.
</p>
<p>
   The executives "are here, just as I am, not because any one
agrees with every last line and jot and tittle of this economic
program," Mr. Clinton acknowledged, but "because it does far more
good than harm."
</p>
<p>
   Despite resistance from some lawmakers in his own party, the
president predicted the bill would pass. "The atmosphere in
discussions here is not as bad as -- if anything, it's a little
better than -- it was before the initial votes were taken in the
Senate and the House," he said. At that time, the package barely
cleared both chambers; Vice President Al Gore's vote was needed to
snap a Senate tie.
</p>
<p>
   Some of the executives who attended yesterday's session weren't a
surprise. Tenneco Inc. Chairman Michael Walsh, for instance, is a
staunch Democrat who provided an early endorsement for Mr. Clinton
during the presidential campaign. Xerox Corp.'s Chairman Paul
Allaire was one of the few top corporate chief executive officers
who contributed money to the Clinton campaign. And others, such as
Atlantic Richfield Co. Chairman Lodwrick M. Cook and Zenith
Electronics Corp. Chairman Jerry Pearlman, have also previously
voiced their approval of Mr. Clinton's economic strategy.
</p>
<p>
   But some faces were fresh. Norman Augustine, the chairman of
defense contractor Martin Marietta Corp., is a registered Republican
who has never stood behind Mr. Clinton. It was also the first formal
show of support by Rand Araskog, the chairman of ITT Corp.
</p>
<p>
   Among those who also attended yesterday's gathering were Dwayne
Andreas, chairman of Archer Daniels Midland Co.; Rodney Chase,
president of BP America Inc.; Ronald Hall, chief executive of Citgo
Petroleum Corp.; Felix Rohatyn, a partner with Lazard Freres & Co.;
Edgar Bronfman Jr., president of Seagram Co.; John Johnson, chairman
of Johnson Publishing Co.; Robert Burt, chairman of FMC Corp.; Ray
Irani, chairman of Occidental Petroleum Corp.; Donald Marron,
chairman of PaineWebber Group Inc.; I. MacAllister Booth, chairman
of Polaroid Corp.; William Smithburg, chairman of Quaker Oats Co.;
Deryck Maughan, chairman of Salomon Brothers Inc.; Philip Carroll,
president of Shell Oil Co.; Robert Campbell, chairman of Sun Co.;
Sheryl Handler, chief executive of Thinking Machines Corp.; and
Gerald Levin, chairman of Time Warner Inc.
</p>
<p>
   Some of the executives also signed letters on behalf of the
Clinton program. Nearly all of them praised the president for his
efforts to pare the deficit.
</p>
<p>
   "This is not necessarily the package I would design," said Martin
Marietta's Mr. Augustine. "But we have to attack the deficit."
</p>
</TXT>
