<HL>    Marketing & Media:
@  Graham Steps Down
@  At Washington Post;
@  Son Is New Chairman </HL>
<DD> 09/10/93 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8 </SO>
<CO>    WPO </CO>
<IN> MEDIA (MED), PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   Washington Post Co. said Katharine Graham stepped
down after 20 years as chairman, and will be succeeded by her son,
Donald E. Graham, the company's chief executive officer.
</p>
<p>
   The departure of the matriarch of the Graham publishing empire
came as little surprise to media analysts, who have been
anticipating Mr. Graham's ascent to the top spot. Mrs. Graham, 76
years old, has not been involved in day-to-day operations at the
company since May 1991, when Mr. Graham assumed the chief executive
officer's title.
</p>
<p>
   In the past several years as the head of Washington Post Co.,
Mrs. Graham directed the expansion of the company's cable television
properties and the acquisition of television stations.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. Graham, 48, will remain the company's chief executive officer
and publisher of the Washington Post newspaper. A company spokesman
said Mr. Graham would now assume more of the traditional functions
handled by the chairman.
</p>
<p>
   Alan G. Spoon, 42, will succeed Mr. Graham as president of the
company. Mr. Spoon became executive vice president and chief
operating officer in May 1991, following a stint as president of
Newsweek, a magazine owned by Washington Post. He retains the title
of chief operating officer.
</p>
<p>
   Mrs. Graham remains a director of the company as chairman of the
board's executive committee, which will also include Messrs. Graham
and Spoon.
</p>
</TXT>
