<HL>    Marketing & Media:
@  Murdoch Completes
@  New York Post Deal
@  As Union Halts Strike </HL>
<DD> 10/04/93 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3 </SO>
<CO>    A.NCP NWS </CO>
<IN> MEDIA (MED), PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   After much melodrama, media baron Rupert Murdoch once
again owns the ailing New York Post.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. Murdoch, chairman and chief executive officer of News Corp.,
completed his $25 million purchase of the bankrupt tabloid Friday,
after threatening twice in recent months to cancel the purchase over
labor disputes. He was lured back last week by promises from nine
craft unions at the Post that they wouldn't honor a strike by the
Newspaper Guild, and once Friday's paper was published without
disruption, Mr. Murdoch closed the deal.
</p>
<p>
   Without support from the other unions, the Guild, which
represents nearly 300 of the Post's 700 employees, voted Saturday to
end its strike. Guild members have been invited to reapply for their
old jobs today, though it is assumed that dozens of them won't be
rehired.
</p>
<p>
   Despite his labor victory, Mr. Murdoch faces major obstacles in
turning around the Post, which has had losses of about $15 million a
year. With the disruptions of multiple owners, bankruptcy and the
retailing recession, both circulation and advertising have fallen
sharply since News Corp. last owned the paper, from 1976 to 1988.
Circulation alone has fallen to about 400,000 from one million a
decade ago. Also, the Post has to compete with two other deep-pocket
tabloid owners, Mortimer B. Zuckerman of New York's Daily News, and
Times Mirror Co., which publishes New York Newsday.
</p>
<p>
   A spokesman for Mr. Murdoch said he believes he can revitalize
the paper while continuing to cut costs. Though the Post might never
be profitable, News Corp. insiders say Mr. Murdoch's goal isn't
merely monetary, but to regain a major metropolitan daily as a
platform for his conservative views.
</p>
</TXT>
