<HL>    Dean Foods Will Buy Birds Eye Brand
@  From Philip Morris Unit for $140 Million
@  ----
@  By Richard Gibson
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 11/02/93 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8 </SO>
<CO>    DF MO </CO>
<IN> FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD), FOOD PRODUCERS, EXCLUDING FISHING (OFP),
   TOBACCO (TOB) </IN>
<TXT>
<p>
   Dean Foods Co., already the country's leading processor of
private-label frozen vegetables, agreed to acquire the Birds Eye
frozen vegetables brand from Philip Morris Cos.' Kraft General Foods
for $140 million.
</p>
<p>
   If approved by federal regulators -- both the company and
industry analysts say they expect no opposition -- the acquisition
would nearly double Dean's vegetable sales and give it the broadest
array of products in the marketplace as well as the oldest name in
the frozen category.
</p>
<p>
   The acquisition would more than double Dean's annual sales of
frozen vegetables, to about $460 million, and increase the company's
portion of the U.S.'s $3.6 billion processed-vegetables market to
nearly 17% from about 10%. For the year ended May 30, Dean reported
vegetable sales of $347 million, or about 15% of its $2.3 billion
total sales. Dean is the nation's second-largest dairy, behind
Borden Inc.
</p>
<p>
   "They offer us all kinds of new blends and value-added products
we're not doing," Howard Dean, chairman and chief executive of the
Franklin Park, Ill., company, said of the acquisition. "We think it
complements our line very well and gives us a great national brand."
</p>
<p>
   Dean hasn't been successful in marketing prepared frozen
vegetables in ready-to-heat sauces, a category in which Birds Eye
has numerous offerings. While the market for plain sliced-and-diced
vegetables has been flat, the one for so-called value-added
products, which also includes vegetables with pasta, is growing.
</p>
<p>
   Dean's major brands include Veg-All canned vegetables and
Freshlike, a frozen and canned line sold primarily in the Midwest.
</p>
<p>
   Kraft said last month it was considering selling Birds Eye, the
No. 2 frozen-vegetables brand in the U.S. behind Grand Metropolitan
PLC's Green Giant. At the time a Kraft executive, explaining the
decision, said, "You can be either really big and develop
significant economies of scale or you can be very focused and go
after segments that are attractive. Where you don't want to be is
somewhere in the middle."
</p>
<p>
   Without a canned line, and bruised in the commodity-like plain
vegetables market, Birds Eye was more susceptible to economic
swings. Lately the vegetable market has been hit by flooding and
fickle consumers. Moreover, where Birds Eye processed only about
one-third of the vegetables it sells, Dean handles crops from field
to supermarket shelf. The Birds Eye acquisition also includes a
small frozen-fruit business.
</p>
<p>
   Investors like the prospects. Dean's stock jumped about 6% on the
news to close at $27.125, up $1.50, in composite New York Stock
Exchange trading.
</p>
<p>
   "It definitely makes sense," said Ravi Sadarangani, food analyst
with William Blair & Co. in Chicago. Buying Birds Eye reduces Dean's
earnings volatility "because Dean has traditionally been in the
private-label segment, where prices are more susceptible to
commodity cycles." Birds Eye's premium products aren't as vulnerable
to such fluctuations, he said.
</p>
<p>
   Food analyst George Dahlman at Piper, Jaffray in Minneapolis
said, "This is a time in the vegetable industry for financially
strong and smart companies to get in deeper. The industry is at a
cyclical bottom so Dean is doubly leveraged to take advantage of
recovery."
</p>
<p>
   The acquisition would include three plants, in Minnesota, New
York and Mexico, increasing Dean's processing facilities to 18. Mr.
Dean said the company intends to retain Birds Eye's production,
sales and distribution force, but to pare some administration
personnel. Birds Eye, now part of Kraft's All-American Gourmet Co.,
is based in Orange, Calif., and has about 900 employees.
</p>
<p>
   Dean was among numerous bidders for Birds Eye, including Unilever
NV, a Dutch company that recently acquired the Breyer's ice cream
business from Kraft.
</p>
</TXT>
