<HL>    Who's News:
@  IBM's Metaphor Cuts Staff </HL>
<DD> 01/13/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8 </SO>
<CO>    IBM </CO>
<IN> COMPUTERS (CPR), SOFTWARE (SOF) </IN>
<DATELINE> MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   International Business Machines Corp.'s
Metaphor Inc. unit said it will shed 80 employees, 20% of its work
force, as part of a restructuring that is separate from IBM overall.
</p>
<p>
   Metaphor, a software subsidiary that IBM purchased in 1991, also
named Chris Grejtak, 43 years old, currently a senior vice
president, president and chief executive officer. He succeeds Cathie
Selleck, 60, who is retiring.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. Grejtak said in an interview that the staff reductions will
affect most areas of the company related to its early proprietary
software products. Metaphor, known for a product called DIS, data
interpretation system, has changed its product line to be less
proprietary and is able to pare back on staff as a result, he said.
