<DOC>
<DOCID> wsj94_012.0142 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940404-0040. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Two Top Woolworth Officers Step Down
@  Amid Probe of Accounting Irregularities
@  ----
@  By Patrick M. Reilly
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 04/04/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3 </SO>
<CO>    Z </CO>
<IN> BROADLINE RETAILERS (RTB) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   The chairman and the chief financial officer of
Woolworth Corp. have temporarily relinquished their posts while the
retailer conducts its investigation into alleged accounting
irregularities.
</p>
<p>
   Woolworth's board named John W. Adams, an outside director, to
serve as interim chairman and chief executive officer while a
special committee, appointed by the board last week and led by Mr.
Adams, investigates the alleged irregularities. Mr. Adams, 69 years
old, is the retired chairman of Canadian-based Emco Ltd., a maker of
plumbing and petroleum equipment; he has served on the Woolworth
board since 1981.
</p>
<p>
   In a statement yesterday, Woolworth said William K. Lavin,
chairman and chief executive, and Charles T. Young, chief financial
officer, stepped down voluntarily on a "temporary basis pending
conclusion" of the investigation.
</p>
<p>
   Messrs. Lavin and Young "deny any wrongdoing" and told the
company "the sole reason for their action is to permit Woolworth to
conduct business as usual" while the investigation proceeds, the
statement said. Mr. Lavin didn't return telephone calls seeking
comment; Mr. Young couldn't be reached for comment. The company said
it expects to name an interim chief financial officer soon.
</p>
<p>
   While the company hasn't commented on the probe, persons close to
the board said that Messrs. Lavin and Young, along with some other
top Woolworth executives, were under investigation by the special
committee for their possible involvement in the alleged
irregularities. The committee is focusing on whether Woolworth
executives knowingly reported inaccurate gross profit margins in at
least three of the company's quarterly reports during the fiscal
year ended Jan. 29. Gross margin is the difference between what the
retailer sold merchandise for and what it actually paid for it, and
is an important component used in calculating a company's net
income.
</p>
<p>
   The committee hired the law firm of Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton
& Garrison and accountant KPMG Peat Marwick to assist in the
investigation. The Paul Weiss partner in charge of the
investigation, Mark A. Belnick, is expected to make a report of the
investigation to Mr. Adams's special committee in six to eight
weeks.
</p>
<p>
   Woolworth has provided few details about the alleged
irregularities, except to say they will cause the retailer to
restate its quarterly results for the last fiscal year, reflecting
the "correction of gross margins." The company has said the
restatements aren't expected to have an impact on the full-year
results. The quarters affected are the first, second and third of
the last fiscal year. People close to the board said the
inaccuracies were corrected during the fourth quarter.
</p>
<p>
   Though the board has been told the margin discrepancies are
modest -- in one quarter the gross margin was misstated by about $16
million -- the board has learned the inaccurate gross margin numbers
probably led Woolworth to report moderate interim after-tax profit
rather than moderate after-tax losses for at least two quarters in
the past fiscal year, according to people familiar with
investigation.
</p>
<p>
   Woolworth, which had revenue last year of close to $10 billion,
is now concerned the news of alleged irregularities could damage its
relationship with suppliers and retail-credit companies. In its
statement yesterday, Woolworth said it reassured several of its
"key" suppliers that the events of the past week won't have any
"material adverse impact on Woolworth's financial position." The
company added that none of the major suppliers contacted "has
indicated that it won't continue to ship to the company." The
statement followed reports in this and other newspapers last week
that several factoring companies and credit services had told
suppliers to hold shipments to Woolworth until details of the
investigation could be learned.
</p>
<p>
   "The allegations have to be put to bed. It's hurting the
company," said a person close to the board. "The credibility
question has to be dealt with." A Woolworth board member, speaking
independently, said, "The company is clean and strong financially,
but this has been a real shakeup."
</p>
<p>
   According to people close to the board, Mr. Adams, who is also
chairman of the board's audit committee, learned of the quarterly
inaccuracies from a "high-level manager" at Woolworth's Manhattan
headquarters in late February. After inquiries, Mr. Adams learned
the allegations had "some substance," the people said. Mr. Adams
then called in the company's standing outside auditor, Price
Waterhouse, and Peat Marwick, to each go over the company's
quarterly statements. Over the weekend of March 26, the two
accounting firms concurred that "sufficient discrepancies" existed
to require a restatement of the company's quarterly numbers for at
least the last fiscal year. Mr. Adams couldn't be reached for
comment.
</p>
<p>
   Though the investigation has barely begun, persons close to the
board said Messrs. Lavin and Young will get a "hard look" as to
whether they were involved, and are both considered a "natural
focus" of the inquiry. The persons added that the investigation will
also include any top Woolworth executives who "had knowledge or
involvement in the reporting of the quarterly numbers."
</p>
<p>
   Indeed, Mr. Lavin and other company executives, are named in a
number of shareholder suits filed late last week in federal court in
Manhattan. Mr. Lavin was Woolworth's chief financial officer for
several years until July 1, 1993, when he was named chairman and
chief executive.
</p>
<p>
   One suit claims Mr. Lavin had access to "adverse" information and
"knew, or was grossly reckless in not knowing, of the fraud
alleged." The suit claims Mr. Lavin acted to "conceal adverse
material information" regarding Woolworth's finances in an effort to
"increase and maintain an artificially high market price for the
common stock of Woolworth."
</p>
<p>
   Other suits charge Woolworth executives and directors sold stock
at prices above last Wednesday's closing price and before the
alleged irregularities came to light. Woolworth shares closed Friday
at $15.125, ending the week down 21%. The shares have plummeted 40%
since Dec. 31.
</p>
<p>
   The investigation follows a wrenching period for Woolworth, whose
origins date back to 1879. Woolworth, attempting to pare away
unprofitable businesses, has spent the past two years selling off
and closing hundreds of its Woolworth variety stores, Kinney shoe
stores, and its Woolco store operation in Canada. The company has
been forced to liquidate many stores and has taken losses reflecting
markdowns, a process some board members believe may have contributed
to reporting inaccurate gross margin numbers.
</p>
<p>
   Board members are mystified as to why executives would knowingly
submit or approve inaccurate gross margins numbers since they have
no connection to executives' compensation, stock-buying plans, or
any other incentives. Executives can earn cash bonuses, but only
based on pretax profit goals determined from year-end audited
results.
</p>
<p>
   "There is no evidence that any of them would have gained
personally from this, or get any advantage," said one board member.
"That's what adds to the mystery here."
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
