<HL>    Cosmic Collision:
@  Apple and Carl Sagan
@  Are Butting Heads
@  ---
@  He Rockets Into Court, Irate
@  Over a Code Name; Some
@  Think It Is a Flameout
@  ----
@  By Jim Carlton
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 04/11/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1 </SO>
<CO>    AAPL </CO>
<IN> COMPUTERS (CPR) </IN>
<DATELINE> SAN FRANCISCO </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   Carl Sagan, the noted astronomer, is a funny
man. Just ask his wife:
</p>
<p>
   "A laugh a minute," she says.
</p>
<p>
   Other people he doesn't always find so amusing. For example: He
does not consider himself a Butt-Head Astronomer, and those who have
intimated that he is have been hauled into court. Sued, by unsmiling
lawyers.
</p>
<p>
   This all began a few months ago. Nerds over at Apple Computer
Inc. were putting together some new computer models. Customarily,
Apple gives these machines secret code names during development, and
real names when they are ready to be sold to the public. Code-naming
is considered an honor. "You pick a name of someone you . . .
respect," explains Mark Macgillivray, a California computer
consultant.
</p>
<p>
   Apple has had computers in the works named after George Gershwin
and Charles Lindbergh. And more recently, somebody plucked out Dr.
Sagan as a code-name honoree. The nerds reportedly jested: Maybe the
name would be lucky, propelling the computers to sales of "billions
and billions." Dr. Sagan, of course, is known for his TV programs
about celestial events "billions and billions of years ago."
</p>
<p>
   Somebody wrote about this in a computer magazine. But when Dr.
Sagan, a Cornell University professor, learned of the purported
honor, he didn't laugh. His lawyers wrote Apple to complain that
this was an illegal usurpation of his name for commercial purposes.
Fine, said Apple.
</p>
<p>
   But the nerds were more mischievous. They changed the code name,
all right. To the abbreviation BHA. When inquiring minds asked what
this meant, they supposedly were told: "Butt-Head Astronomer."
</p>
<p>
   This traveled at light speed to the 59-year-old astronomer. He
sued Apple last week in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. The suit
contends that calling Dr. Sagan a "Butt-Head Astronomer" is
"defamatory on its face" and has subjected him to "hatred, contempt,
ridicule and obloquy." He is seeking unspecified damages. Dr. Sagan
wasn't available and his lawyer declined to comment. Apple won't,
either, though a spokesman -- contrary to previous accounts -- says
the BHA designation that replaced the Sagan code name was "randomly
chosen."
</p>
<p>
   Some lawyers expect Dr. Sagan's suit to flame out. It is doubtful
that an unofficial code name is a commercial use of his name, they
say. And, under recent U.S. Supreme Court rulings on libel, it is
unlikely that "butt-head" will be seen as defamatory, says Kevin
Baine, a Washington lawyer. "If you refer to someone as a butt-head,
ordinarily speaking, no one is going to take that as any specific
charge of any improper conduct or insinuation of any character
trait," he says.
</p>
<p>
   A big question, Mr. Baine says, that would have to be answered at
trial: What exactly is a butt-head, anyway? As portrayed by the
demonic characters on MTV's "Beavis and Butt-head" cartoon series, a
butt-head is a wise-cracking lout. Not so, says Laid Back
Enterprises in Oklahoma City, which claims a trademark on an amiable
cartoon character named "Butthead." "We consider our Butthead to be
an endearing, fun-loving guy," a spokesman says.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
